<h1>Problem 2250 - Codeforces 2109C3, adapted, NC</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(n\) be a positive integer. Alice chooses a positive integer \(x< 10^9\) and writes it down on a piece of paper, which Bob can&#x27;t see. In each step Bob can now do 1 of 3 moves: <ul><li>ask Alice to multiply the last added number on the paper by some positive integer \(k\), and write down the new number on the paper</li><li>ask Alice to add some integer \(k\) to the last added number on the paper and write down the new number on the paper</li><li>ask Alice to write down the sum of digits of the last added number on the paper</li></ul> What is the minimal number of moves so that Bob can guarantee that \(n\) is written down on the paper (in terms of \(n\))?</p>
